;; 05-where-to-read-config.book.slatl
;; Book of Systems — Chapter 5

(chapter
  :book             "Book of Systems"
  :chapter-number   5
  :title            "Where To Read Config"
  :audience         "Motoi Copilot + Motoi engineers"
  :dialect          "motoi"
  :date             "2026-07-16"
  :status           "authored, first pass"
  :prose
"Config is the small set of choices the Copilot needs at startup:
default theme, whether to speak aloud, whether to auto-save, the
name of the user's project, that kind of thing. This chapter is
about where config lives and, more importantly, where it does not.

The rule: **app-local only.** The Copilot does not read
system-wide config. It does not read another app's config. It does
not walk up the directory tree looking for a `.motoi/` folder in
a parent. Config lives in exactly one place, decided by the host
at startup, and read once.

Per host, the honest answer is:

- `phone-ios`, `tablet-ipad`, `phone-android`, `tablet-android`:
  The app has no separate config directory; config is a file in
  the data directory, named `config.slat`, and read like any
  other user data. Mobile OSes do not have a per-app config
  location outside the app's private area.

- `computer-macos`:
  `~/Library/Application Support/<AppName>/config.slat`.

- `computer-linux`:
  `${XDG_CONFIG_HOME:-~/.config}/<AppName>/config.slat`. Note
  this is different from XDG_DATA_HOME (Chapter 4). On Linux,
  config and data are conventionally kept in separate trees.

- `computer-windows`:
  `%APPDATA%\\<AppName>\\config.slat`. Same tree as data on
  Windows — the OS does not split them.

- `unknown`:
  `./motoi-data/config.slat`. Same directory as data.

The Copilot never reads `/etc/motoi.conf` or `~/.motoirc` or a
system-wide plist. There is no such file. If someone puts one
there, the Copilot ignores it.

Read pattern, with the same environment-variable discipline:

```scheme
(define (motoi/config-dir)
  (or (get-environment-variable \"MOTOI_CONFIG_DIR\")
      (motoi/data-dir)))

(define (motoi/config-path)
  (string-append (motoi/config-dir) \"/config.slat\"))
```

Because config is small and read rarely, the Copilot loads it
once at startup and holds it in a value. It does not re-read
config from disk during a session. If the user changes a config,
the Copilot picks it up on the next launch. Live config reload
is a feature the Copilot does not have; asking for it goes to
escalation.

Missing config is normal. On first launch, `config.slat` does
not exist. The Copilot handles this with a small default:

```scheme
(define (motoi/default-config)
  '((theme      light)
    (voice      off)
    (auto-save  #t)
    (locale     unknown)))

;; Reading (pseudo-shape; the actual read is via slat-load):
(define config
  (motoi/default-config))
```

The default config is spelled out in code, in one place, and every
other module reads config through that value. This is how the
Copilot avoids the classic bug of half-configured startup: there
is no such state. Either the file loaded, or the defaults did.
The Copilot never runs on a mixture.

What the config does not hold: any secret, any credential, any
API key. The Copilot has no verb to speak to a service that
requires a credential, so it has nothing to store. If a future
adapter needs credentials, the credentials live in the host's
keystore and the Copilot asks for them at use-time via escalation.
It does not persist them in the config file.")
